%[text] # Part 3 Optimization Exercise V2 - Start from PCB Antenna Designer Session
%[text] In this exercise, you start from a saved PCB Antenna Designer session that already contains the H-notch patch geometry and design variables. We are going to use the **Optimize** workflow available in the app.
%[text] 
%[text] The session file for this exercise is:  `HNotchPatchSession.mat`
%%
%[text] ## Open PCB Antenna Designer
%[text] Run this command to open the app.
pcbAntennaDesigner
%%
%[text] ## Load the Saved Session
%[text] In PCB Antenna Designer, use **Open Session** and select `HNotchPatchSession/HNotchPatchSession.mat`
%[text] ![](text:image:74cb)
%[text] After the session opens, verify these items before optimization:
%[text] 
%[text] - The H-notch patch geometry appears in the 3-D view.
%[text] - The **Design Variables** table is populated.
%[text] - Patch and notch dimensions are linked to design variables, not plain numeric constants.
%[text] - The feed center is `[-3,-3]` mm and the feed connects the H-notch layer to the ground plane. \
%%
%[text] ## Set Baseline Analysis Frequencies
%[text] Before optimization, go to the **Analysis** tab and set these values so baseline plots use the same frequencies as the optimization.
%[text] 
%[text] - **Center Frequency**: `4.5` GHz
%[text] - **Frequency Range**: 4.38:0.04:4.62 GHz \
centerFrequencyGHz = 4.65
frequencyRangeGHz = 4.38:0.04:4.62
%[text] ![](text:image:5420)
%%
%[text] ## Run Baseline Analysis
%[text] In the **Analysis** tab, run these plots before optimization:
%[text] 
%[text] - **Impedance**
%[text] - **S Parameter**
%[text] - **3D Pattern** \
%[text] 
%[text] These baseline plots give you a before/after comparison after the optimizer updates the design variables.
%%
%[text] ## Open the Optimization Workflow
%[text] Click **Optimize** in the app toolstrip. In the **OBJECTIVE FUNCTION** gallery, choose **Maximize Gain**.
%[text] ![](text:image:51da)
%[text] Keep the main lobe direction at `[0 90]` unless the instructor asks you to optimize a different pattern direction.
mainLobeDirection = [0 90]
%%
%[text] ## Select Design Variables
%[text] On the optimizer **Design Variables** tab, check only the four H-notch patch dimensions shown below. Enter the lower and upper bounds in millimeters.
%[text:table]
%[text] | Design Variable | Initial Value | Lower Bound | Upper Bound |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | `Length` | `20` | `19` | `24` |
%[text] | `Width` | `20` | `16` | `21` |
%[text] | `NotchLength` | `6` | `5.4` | `6.6` |
%[text] | `NotchWidth` | `6` | `5.4` | `6.6` |
%[text:table]
%[text] ![](text:image:426a)
%[text] Leave board dimensions, feed location, ground plane dimensions, and center coordinates unchecked for this exercise.
optimizationVariableNames = ["Length","Width","NotchLength","NotchWidth"];
optimizationBoundsMillimeters = [19 16 5.4 5.4; 24 21 6.6 6.6]
%%
%[text] ## Add the S11 Constraint
%[text] On the optimizer **Constraints** tab, configure the impedance-bandwidth constraint.
%[text] 
%[text] - **Constraint Function**: `S11 (dB)`
%[text] - **Sign**: `<`
%[text] - **Value**: `-8`
%[text] - **Weight**: `100` \
constraintFunction = "S11 (dB)";
constraintSign = "<";
constraintValue = -8
constraintWeight = 100
%[text] ![](text:image:1e75)
%[text] 
%[text] Click **Apply**
%%
%[text] ## Choose Optimization Options
%[text] In the optimizer settings area, use these options:
%[text] - **Optimizer**: `SADEA`
%[text] - **Iterations**: `100`
%[text] - **Parallel Computing**: leave unchecked unless the instructor asks you to use a local parallel pool \
optimizerName = "SADEA";
iterations = 100
%%
%[text] ## Apply and Run
%[text] Click **Apply** after entering the objective, design variables, and constraint. Then click the green **Run** button to start SADEA optimization.
%[text] 
%[text] During optimization, the app first builds a surrogate model from sampled designs. After that, it runs optimizer iterations and updates the convergence plot.
%[text] 
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Accept the Optimized Design
%[text] When optimization completes, click **Accept** to return to the analysis workflow with the optimized dimensions applied to the antenna.
%[text] 
%[text] Record the optimized values for `Length`, `Width`, `NotchLength`, and `NotchWidth` in your notes.
%%
%[text] ## Validate the Optimized Antenna
%[text] In the **Analysis** tab, rerun **Impedance**, **S Parameter**, and **3D Pattern**. Compare the optimized result with the baseline result.
%[text] 
%[text] - Does the optimized antenna satisfy `S11 < -8 dB` over any part of `4:0.1:5` GHz?
%[text] - Did the peak gain or selected main-lobe gain improve?
%[text] - Which design variable changed the most? \
%%
%[text] ## Export the Result
%[text] Export the optimized antenna from PCB Antenna Designer to the MATLAB workspace. Use a clear variable name such as `hNotchAntOptimized`, then save the antenna by itself so the exported MAT-file can also be imported by PCB Antenna Designer later.
if exist("hNotchAntOptimized","var")
    save("HNotchPatchUnitElement_Optimized.mat","hNotchAntOptimized")
else
    disp("Export the optimized antenna from PCB Antenna Designer as hNotchAntOptimized, then rerun this section.")
end
